<td width=50%><font color=white>Posted By: Relvart</font></td><td width=50% align=right><font color=white>2000-01-30 15:58:02</font></td></tr><tr>
<td colspan=2 bgcolor="#0000AF"><font color=white>Where do you get the molds for these and what skill do you need to make them?<BR>
</font></td></tr></table>
<BR>
<table width=100%>
<tr>
<td width=50%><font color=white>Posted By: Tymat</font></td><td width=50% align=right><font color=white>2000-01-31 17:59:16</font></td></tr><tr>
<td colspan=2 bgcolor="#0000AF"><font color=white>Blacksmithing Skill, molds sold in Wk, Halas, Freeport, etc. THe cool thing about these are that on Tallon Zek, I could (and did) sell them for 40pp+ to PvP orientated druids that wanted to fool their opposition. They look like level 10 newbies with their leather armor, and what looks like a longsword. =) I made a lot, off a smart move. Too bad, the cat is out of the bag now, eh?</font></td></tr></table>
<BR>
<table width=100%>
<tr>
<td width=50%><font color=white>Posted By: Kannin</font></td><td width=50% align=right><font color=white>2000-02-03 16:28:00</font></td></tr><tr>
<td colspan=2 bgcolor="#0000AF"><font color=white>I recently switched to using this sword rather than my normal mino battle axe.  I must say it is quite the improvement for me.  The delay is much less, and i hit for only 1-2 points of damage less than the axe.  I would reccomend the switch from the mino axe to this sword to any ranger thinking about a switch.</font></td></tr></table>
<BR>
<table width=100%>
<tr>
<td width=50%><font color=white>Posted By: kulothar</font></td><td width=50% align=right><font color=white>2000-02-17 15:49:19</font></td></tr><tr>
<td colspan=2 bgcolor="#0000AF"><font color=white>Druids love this and the parrying dagger as a great disguise or novelty. Since druids look like newbies until the upper 40+ levels attacking a rogue or fighter newbie could hold a big supprise in +PVP. The only better one is carrying the Pestilence Scythe that is druid weildable (there are two versions of the scythe) which makes you look like a newbie ranger.  The damage ratio on these are not as good as combine but They do pay for themselves and help raise blacksmithing.   </font></td></tr></table>
